# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: animal-euthanasia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:animal-euthanasia/1994-oregon-ballot-measure-16] The measure was narrowly approved in the November 8, 1994, general election.
[src:animal-euthanasia/1994-oregon-ballot-measure-16] An injunction delayed implementation of the Act until it was lifted on October 27, 1997.
[src:animal-euthanasia/1994-oregon-ballot-measure-16] **Measure 51**, referred in the wake of the US Supreme Court's 1997 ruling in *Washington v.
[src:animal-euthanasia/1994-oregon-ballot-measure-16] Glucksberg* by the state legislature in November 1997, sought to repeal the Death with Dignity Act, but was rejected by nearly 60% of voters.
[src:animal-euthanasia/1994-oregon-ballot-measure-16] Bush administration, but was upheld by the Supreme Court of the United States in *Gonzales v.
[src:animal-euthanasia/1994-oregon-ballot-measure-16] Under the law, any competent adult who has been diagnosed, by a physician, with a terminal illness that will kill the patient within six months may request in writing, from his or her physician, a prescription for a lethal dose of medication for the purpose of ending the patient's life.
[src:animal-euthanasia/1994-oregon-ballot-measure-16] Exercise of the option under this law is voluntary and the patient must initiate the request.
[src:animal-euthanasia/1994-oregon-ballot-measure-16] Any physician, pharmacist, or other healthcare provider who has moral objections has the right to refuse to participate.
[src:animal-euthanasia/1994-oregon-ballot-measure-16] The request must be confirmed by two witnesses, at least one of whom is not related to the patient, is not entitled to any portion of the patient's estate, is not the patient's physician, and is not employed by a health care facility caring for the patient.
[src:animal-euthanasia/1994-oregon-ballot-measure-16] After the request is made, another physician must examine the patient's medical records and confirm the diagnosis.
[src:animal-euthanasia/1994-oregon-ballot-measure-16] The patient must be determined to be free of a mental condition impairing judgment.
[src:animal-euthanasia/1994-oregon-ballot-measure-16] Should either physician have concerns about the patient's ability to make an informed decision, or feel the patient's request may be motivated by depression or coercion, the patient must be referred for a psychological evaluation.
[src:animal-euthanasia/1994-oregon-ballot-measure-16] The law protects doctors from liability for providing a lethal prescription for a terminally ill, competent adult in compliance with the statute's restrictions.
[src:animal-euthanasia/1994-oregon-ballot-measure-16] Participation by physicians, pharmacists, and health care providers is voluntary.
[src:animal-euthanasia/1994-oregon-ballot-measure-16] From the beginning of 1999 through the end of 2024, a total of 4,881 people have had prescriptions written and 3,243 patients have died from ingesting medications prescribed under the act.
[src:animal-euthanasia/1994-oregon-ballot-measure-16] The median age of the 3,243 patients who died from ingesting medication was 73; 69.2 percent of patients had malignant neoplasms (cancer).
[src:animal-euthanasia/1994-oregon-ballot-measure-16] Of the 3,243, 53.1% were male (46.9% female); 45.1% had a Baccalaureate degree or higher; 45.2% were married; primary end of life concerns were loss of autonomy (90.1%), inability to make life enjoyable (89.4%), and loss of dignity (69.4%).
[src:animal-euthanasia/1994-oregon-ballot-measure-16] The Death with Dignity Act was the basis of the Washington Death with Dignity Act in 2008.
[src:animal-euthanasia/1994-oregon-ballot-measure-16] In 2011 the documentary film *How to Die in Oregon* was released.
[src:animal-euthanasia/1994-oregon-ballot-measure-16] It won the Grand Jury prize for documentary film at the 27th Sundance Film Festival.
[src:animal-euthanasia/1994-oregon-ballot-measure-16] According to Dignity in Dying, Lord Falconer's Assisted Dying Bill, first tabled in the House of Lords in June 2014, "draws on the experience" of the Death with Dignity Act.
[src:animal-euthanasia/1994-oregon-ballot-measure-16] In addition to arguments against physician-assisted dying, opponents feared that terminally ill people throughout the nation would flock to Oregon to take advantage of the law.
[src:animal-euthanasia/1994-oregon-ballot-measure-16] This fear has not been realized, largely because drafters of the law limited its use to Oregon residents.
[src:animal-euthanasia/1994-oregon-ballot-measure-16] Despite the measure's passage, implementation was tied up in the courts for several years.
[src:animal-euthanasia/1994-oregon-ballot-measure-16] In 1997, the Oregon Legislative Assembly referred Measure 51, which would have repealed the act, to the ballot.
[src:animal-euthanasia/1994-oregon-ballot-measure-16] Proponents of Measure 51 argued that the Death with Dignity Act lacked a mandatory counseling provision, a family notification provision, strong reporting requirements, or a strong residency requirement.
[src:animal-euthanasia/1994-oregon-ballot-measure-16] Measure 51 opponents argued that sending the measure back to voters was disrespectful considering they had already passed Measure 16 via the initiative process.
[src:animal-euthanasia/1994-oregon-ballot-measure-16] They also felt that the safeguards in the Death with Dignity Act were adequate.
[src:animal-euthanasia/1994-oregon-ballot-measure-16] Measure 51 was defeated in the November 4, 1997, special election with 445,830 votes in favor, and 666,275 votes against.
[src:animal-euthanasia/1994-oregon-ballot-measure-16] Some members of the United States Congress, notably Senator Don Nickles of Oklahoma, tried to block implementation of Measure 16, but failed.
[src:animal-euthanasia/1994-oregon-ballot-measure-16] Jones blocked a move by United States Attorney General John Ashcroft to suspend the license for prescribing drugs covered in the Controlled Substances Act of doctors who prescribed life-ending medications under the Oregon law.
[src:animal-euthanasia/1994-oregon-ballot-measure-16] The Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals affirmed the block, stating that the "Attorney General lacked Congress' requisite authorization".
[src:animal-euthanasia/1994-oregon-ballot-measure-16] Supreme Court heard arguments in the case of *Gonzales v.
[src:animal-euthanasia/1994-oregon-ballot-measure-16] Oregon* to determine the fate of the Death with Dignity law.
[src:animal-euthanasia/1994-oregon-ballot-measure-16] Arguing on behalf of the state was Oregon Senior Assistant Attorney General Robert Atkinson.
[src:animal-euthanasia/1994-oregon-ballot-measure-16] Oregon's five Democratic members of Congress also filed a brief in support of the State's position.
[src:animal-euthanasia/1994-oregon-ballot-measure-16] United States Solicitor General Paul Clement argued on behalf of the Bush administration, which challenged Oregon's right to regulate the practice of medicine when that practice entails prescribing federally controlled substances.
[src:animal-euthanasia/1994-oregon-ballot-measure-16] On January 17, 2006, the court ruled 6–3 in favor of Oregon, upholding the law.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Robert Morris (1703–1754) was an English writer on architecture.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] His published works include *Lectures on Architecture* (1734–36), *An Essay on Harmony* (1739), and *The Art of Architecture* (1742).
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also wrote poems, essays, and pamphlets, and worked as a surveyor.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] According to Adams, Morris encountered *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood* in 1745.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Expecting an argument against flesh-eating, he instead found a defence of meat consumption based on a post-Flood reading of Genesis.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris disagreed with that interpretation and wrote a reply, which was published in 1746 as *A Reasonable Plea for the Animal Creation*.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] The treatise is made up of a preface, a letter to General Foliot, nine letters addressed to a friend, and a concluding reply to *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood*.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams writes that the central part of the book consists of letters Morris had written in 1737 and 1738 and later incorporated into the printed work.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris argues that humans have no natural right to kill animals for food.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He appeals both to Genesis and to "the nature and reason of things", maintaining that the food originally given to humans was the produce of the earth.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He rejects attempts to justify meat-eating through scripture, custom, bodily necessity, or animal predation.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also argues that humans are not naturally fitted for carnivory, and describes butchery and cookery as artificial practices rather than natural ones.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Drawing on writers such as Pythagoras and Plutarch, he attributes feeling and a degree of rationality to animals and treats their destruction for food as a matter of cruelty and injustice.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In her introduction to the 2005 republication, Carol J.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams describes the treatise as a neglected contribution to 18th-century vegetarian and animal-ethical writing.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She argues that Morris' case against flesh-eating is centred less on health than on moral obligation, and that his appeal to the "light of Nature" gives the work a distinctive place among early vegetarian texts.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams also comments on the book's epistolary form, noting that its letters are addressed to a flesh-eating friend.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She treats that structure as part of the book's argument, since Morris repeatedly answers objections and defends vegetarianism against the assumptions of a meat-eating society.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She further notes Morris' rejection of claims of human superiority and his attribution of sentience and reason to animals.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] On Adams' reading, these features connect the treatise to later debates in animal ethics.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Before its republication in 2005, the treatise had appeared only occasionally in modern writing.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Whisker, John Simons, and Rod Preece each referred to it as an early contribution to vegetarian and animal-ethical thought.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Simons described Morris, together with John Hildrop, as a precursor to Humphry Primatt.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Preece quoted from the treatise and placed Morris among earlier writers who argued for vegetarianism on ethical grounds, including John Oswald, George Nicholson, Joseph Ritson, and John Frank Newton.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In 2005, the treatise was republished in *Organization & Environment* with an introductory article by Carol J.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Francis Hutcheson (1694–1746) was a philosopher of the Scottish Enlightenment and professor of moral philosophy at the University of Glasgow.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He was a leading defender of moral sense theory, according to which moral judgement arises from an innate sense rather than from reason alone.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He began work on *A System of Moral Philosophy* in 1738 and continued revising it until his death.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In *A System of Moral Philosophy*, Hutcheson sets out a broad account of ethics, natural law, private rights, and political society.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The first book concerns human nature and the supreme good.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses the faculties of the mind, the affections, and the will, and restates his view that human beings possess a moral sense by which they approve virtue and disapprove vice.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He argues that virtue is grounded in benevolence directed by reason, and relates moral life to providence and natural religion.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The second book deals with natural law and private rights.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses obligation, contracts, property, promises, oaths, and legal duties.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He distinguishes between perfect and imperfect rights, and treats justice as distinct from broader duties of benevolence.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He also argues that laws should answer to reason, public good, and natural equity.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The third book turns to civil society and government.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson examines the basis of political authority, the forms of government, and topics including marriage, family, slavery, taxation, magistracy, war, and civil law.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He holds that political power must be exercised for the common good and with the consent of the governed.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Modern commentators have drawn attention to Hutcheson's discussion of animals in the *System*.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In a 2007 article, Aaron Garrett argued that Hutcheson offered an early argument for animal rights by grounding moral consideration in sentience and the capacity to suffer rather than in rational agency alone.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Garrett also compared Hutcheson's treatment of animals with his discussion of infants, and placed him in a line of thought distinct from Lockean rights theory.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Michael Bradie likewise noted that Hutcheson treated cruelty to animals as morally wrong because animals are capable of suffering.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] At the same time, Bradie argued that Hutcheson retained a hierarchical account in which human beings, because of their superior rational capacities, may use animals when necessary.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Bradie described this position as an early attempt to balance human interests with concern for animal suffering.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Foulis in Glasgow and distributed in London by A.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] It appeared in two volumes in 1755, five years after Hutcheson's death; it was published posthumously by his son Francis Hutcheson the younger, from the original manuscript.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A new edition was published in 2000 by Thoemmes, with an introduction by Daniel Carey, and was later republished by A & C Black in 2006.
[src:animal-euthanasia/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A further edition was issued by Cambridge University Press in 2015.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abandoned-pets] Animal welfare laws in many states of the United States make it a crime to abandon a pet.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abandoned-pets] Often, when abandoned, pets are forced to fend for themselves and become stray or feral.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abandoned-pets] Feral cats are said to outnumber feral dogs and can become challenging to handle and socialize enough to be re-introduced to a new human owner.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abandoned-pets] In general, only some newly abandoned cats and very young feral kittens can be tamed.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abandoned-pets] There is a necessity to investigate interventions to prevent companion-animal relinquishment.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abandoned-pets] Stray animals increase potential exposure to zoonotic diseases like rabies.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abandoned-pets] Cat bites or scratches involving stray or feral animals are eight times more common than dog bites.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abandoned-pets] The impacts of dog and cat predation on wildlife can also be significant.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abandoned-pets] Some pets relinquished to an animal shelter will be euthanized due to a lack of space or financial resources.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abandoned-pets] Millions of companion animals enter animal shelters every year in the United States.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abandoned-pets] However, the number of dogs and cats euthanized in US shelters declined from approximately 2.6 million in 2011 to 1.5 million in 2018.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abandoned-pets] This decline can be partially explained by an increase in the percentage of animals adopted, and an increase in the number of stray animals successfully returned to their owners.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abandoned-pets] Studies show that the majority of people who relinquish an animal also report being emotionally attached to the animal.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abandoned-pets] It has been reported that when forced to abandon their animals in an evacuation, people suffer mental issues such as grief, depression, and post-traumatic stress disorder.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abandoned-pets] Recognizing the importance of pets to their owners and their role in public health is an essential first step in improving a public health problem that has been seen repeatedly in the past and is unlikely to change in the future.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abandoned-pets] Pet abandonment increased during the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abandoned-pets] In early 2009, the ASPCA published advice for people facing foreclosure and the loss of their pets, recommending finding a foster or adoption situation for your pet, being aware of rental property rules for pets, and checking with animal shelters and animal rescue groups.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists disagree on the strategy that must be used to achieve their goal.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists such as Steven Best and David Nibert argue, respectively, that embracing alliance politics and militant direct action for change (including civil disobedience, mass confrontation, etc), and transcending capitalism are integral to ending animal exploitation.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists generally oppose movements that seek to make animal use more humane or to abolish specific forms of animal use, since they believe this undermines the movement to abolish all forms of animal use.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abolitionism-animal-rights] The objective is to secure a moral and legal paradigm shift, whereby animals are no longer regarded as things to be owned and used.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abolitionism-animal-rights] The American philosopher Tom Regan writes that abolitionists want empty cages, not bigger ones.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abolitionism-animal-rights] This is contrasted with animal welfare, which seeks incremental reform, and animal protectionism, which seeks to combine the first principles of abolitionism with an incremental approach, but which is regarded by some abolitionists as another form of welfarism or "New Welfarism".
[src:animal-euthanasia/abolitionism-animal-rights] The word relates to the historical term abolitionism—a social movement to end slavery or human ownership of other humans.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abolitionism-animal-rights] Based on the way of evaluating welfare reforms, abolitionists can be either radical or pragmatic.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abolitionism-animal-rights] While the former maintain that welfare reforms can only be dubiously described as moral improvements, the latter consider welfare reforms as moral improvements even when the conditions they permit are unjust.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abolitionism-animal-rights] He calls such groups the "new welfarists", arguing that, though their aim is an end to animal use, the reforms they pursue are indistinguishable from reforms agreeable to traditional welfarists, who he says have no interest in abolishing animal use.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abolitionism-animal-rights] He argues that reform campaigns entrench the property status of animals, and validate the view that animals simply need to be treated better.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abolitionism-animal-rights] Instead, he writes, the public's view that animals can be used and consumed ought to be challenged.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abolitionism-animal-rights] His position is that this should be done by promoting ethical veganism.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abolitionism-animal-rights] Others think that this should be done by creating a public debate in society.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abolitionism-animal-rights] He rhetorically asks, how can one hope to create some consumer base for this new vegan world when over a billion people live on less than a dollar a day?
[src:animal-euthanasia/abolitionism-animal-rights] Nibert acknowledges that post-capitalism on its own will not automatically end animal exploitation or bring about a more just world, but that it is a "necessary precondition" for such changes.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abolitionism-animal-rights] New welfarists argue that there is no logical or practical contradiction between abolitionism and "welfarism".
[src:animal-euthanasia/abolitionism-animal-rights] Welfarists think that they can be working toward abolition, but by gradual steps, pragmatically taking into account what most people can be realistically persuaded to do in the short as well as the long term, and reduce animal suffering as it is most urgent to relieve.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abolitionism-animal-rights] People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals, for example, in addition to promoting local improvements in the treatment of animals, promote vegetarianism.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abolitionism-animal-rights] Although some people believe that changing the legal status of nonhuman sentient beings is a first step in abolishing ownership or mistreatment, others argue that this will not succeed if the consuming public has not already begun to reduce or eliminate its exploitation of animals for food.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 1992, Switzerland amended its constitution to recognize animals as *beings* and not *things*.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abolitionism-animal-rights] The dignity of animals is also protected in Switzerland.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abolitionism-animal-rights] New Zealand granted basic rights to five great ape species in 1999.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abolitionism-animal-rights] Their use is now forbidden in research, testing or teaching.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abolitionism-animal-rights] Germany added animal welfare in a 2002 amendment to its constitution, becoming the first European Union member to do so.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2007, the parliament of the Balearic Islands, an autonomous province of Spain, passed the world's first legislation granting legal rights to all great apes.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2013, India officially recognized dolphins as non-human persons.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2014, France revised the legal status of animals from movable property to sentient beings.
[src:animal-euthanasia/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2015, the province of Quebec in Canada adopted the Animal Welfare and Safety Act, which gave animals the legal status of "sentient beings with biological needs".
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] Euthanasia is often used to end an animal's suffering from terminal, incurable (and especially painful) conditions or diseases, when there is a lack of resources to continue supporting the animal, or at the end of laboratory test procedures.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] For domesticated animals, the discussion of animal euthanasia is often substituted with euphemisms, such as "put down" or "put to sleep".
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] The methods of euthanasia can be divided into pharmacological and physical methods.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] Acceptable pharmacological methods include injected drugs and gases that first depress the central nervous system and then cardiovascular activity.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] Acceptable physical methods must first cause rapid loss of consciousness by disrupting the central nervous system.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] The most common methods are discussed here, but other acceptable methods are used in different situations.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] Upon administration of intravenous anesthetic, unconsciousness, followed by respiratory and then cardiac arrest, occurs rapidly, usually within 30 seconds.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] The two-stage process that some veterinarians use includes a first shot that is a sedative to make the animal more comfortable, and then a second shot that euthanizes the animal.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] This allows the owner the chance to say goodbye to a live pet without their emotions stressing the animal.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] It also greatly mitigates any tendency toward spasm and other involuntary movements, which tends to increase the emotional upset that the pet's owner experiences.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] For large animals, the volumes of barbiturates required are considered by some to be impractical, although this is standard practice in the United States.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] For horses and cattle, other drugs may be available.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] Occasionally, a horse injected with these mixtures may display apparent seizure activity before death.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] This may be due to premature cardiac arrest.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] However, if typical precautions (e.g., sedation with detomidine) are taken, this is rarely a problem.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] Anecdotal reports that long-term use of phenylbutazone increases the risk of this reaction are unverified.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] After an animal has died, it is not uncommon for the body to exhibit postmortem jerks or a sudden bladder or postmortem bowel evacuation.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] This is caused by the muscles of the deceased animal's body relaxing.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] Gas anesthetics such as isoflurane and sevoflurane can be used for euthanasia of very small animals.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] The animals are placed in sealed chambers where high levels of anesthetic gas are introduced.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] Death may also be caused using carbon dioxide once unconsciousness has been achieved by inhalation of an anesthetic.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] Carbon dioxide is often used on its own for the euthanasia of wild animals.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] There are mixed opinions on whether it causes distress when used on its own, with human experiments lending support to the evidence that it can cause distress and equivocal results in non-humans.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] In 2013, the American Veterinary Medical Association (AVMA) issued new guidelines for carbon dioxide induction, stating that a flow rate of 10% to 30% volume/min is optimal for the humane euthanasia of small rodents.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] Carbon monoxide is often used, but some states in the US have banned its use in animal shelters.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] Although carbon monoxide poisoning is not particularly painful, the conditions in the gas chamber are often not humane.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] Nitrogen is effective, although some young animals are more resistant to the effects, and it is currently not widely used.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] The use of gas chambers is not the most humane form of euthanasia, as it can take up to 20 minutes to fully euthanize the animal.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] If the chambers are not calibrated correctly or the animal is ill, the process is only delayed further, which can cause more harm to the animal.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] Cervical dislocation, or displacement (breaking or fracturing) of the neck, is an older and less common method of killing small animals such as mice.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] When performed properly, it is intended to cause a death that is as painless as possible with no cost or equipment involved.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] The handler must know the proper method to perform the procedure—without proper training and method education, there is a risk of causing severe pain and suffering instead of death.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] It is unknown how long an animal remains conscious, or the level of suffering it experiences after a proper snap of the neck, which is why it has become less common and is often replaced with inhalants.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] When intravenous injection is not possible, euthanasia drugs such as pentobarbital can be injected directly into a heart chamber or body cavity.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] Concerning state and federal laws, one of the most humane forms of euthanizing animals is through the injection of sodium pentobarbital.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] This is typically the second shot that is administered after a sedative when euthanizing animals.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] Intraperitoneal (IP) injection is the injection of a substance into the abdominal cavity, and may take up to 15 minutes to take effect in dogs and cats While IP injections are fully acceptable, an intracardiac (IC) injection may only be performed on an unconscious or deeply sedated animal.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] Performing IC injections on a fully conscious animal in places with humane laws for animal handling is often a criminal offense.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] This can be a means of euthanasia for large animals—such as horses, cattle, and deer—if performed properly.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] The risks are minimal if carried out by skilled personnel in a suitable location.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] to slaughter cattle and other livestock.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] Horses are killed outright by the captive bolt, making pithing and exsanguination unnecessary.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] Small animal euthanasia is typically performed in a veterinary clinic or hospital, at animal shelter, or at the pet owner's home.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] It is usually carried out by a veterinarian or a veterinary technician working under the veterinarian's supervision.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] Often, animal shelter workers are trained to perform euthanasia as well.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] A licensed veterinarian can help an owner determine when, in the course of an illness or behavioral problem, euthanasia is appropriate.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] Large animals with severe injuries are often euthanized at the site of the accident.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] Some animal rights organizations support animal euthanasia in certain circumstances and practice euthanasia at shelters that they operate.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] In the U.S., for companion animals euthanized in animal shelters, most states prescribe intravenous injection as the required method.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] These laws date to 1990, when Georgia's Humane Euthanasia Act became the first state law to mandate this method.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] Before that, gas chambers and other methods were commonly used.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] The Georgia law was resisted by the Georgia Commissioner of Agriculture, Tommy Irvin, who was charged with enforcing the act.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] In March 2007, he was sued by former State Representative Chesley V.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] Morton, who wrote the law, and subsequently ordered by the court to enforce all provisions of the Act.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] Some states allow the use of carbon monoxide chambers for euthanasia.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] In the Philippines, the treatment and handling of stray dogs are governed by specific laws that emphasize animal welfare.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] 8485, also known as the "Animal Welfare Act of 1998," as amended by Republic Act No.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] This law outlines the responsibilities of local government units (LGUs) and veterinarians in dealing with stray animals.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] Many pet owners choose to have their pets cremated or buried after the pet is euthanized.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] There are pet funeral homes that specialize in animal burial or cremation.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] Otherwise, the animal facility will often freeze the body and subsequently send it to the local landfill.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] In some instances, animals euthanized at shelters or animal control agencies have been sent to meat rendering facilities to be processed for use in cosmetics, fertilizer, gelatin, poultry feed, pharmaceuticals and pet food.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] It was proposed that the presence of pentobarbital in dog food may have caused dogs to become less responsive to the drug when being euthanized.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] However, a 2002 FDA study found no dog or cat DNA in the foods they tested, so it was theorized that the drug found in dog food came from euthanized cattle and horses.
[src:animal-euthanasia/animal-euthanasia] Furthermore, the drug level found in pet food was safe.
